texts.name: Our colors convey our brand personality, values and help our fans navigate our digital interface. The right combination of colors can influence how they feel, think, and interact with our site. Using color at the right time and place is key to this experience.

texts.name: Neptune blue is our primary color, and it's also our brand colour. We use it for all our main CTA buttons and across our brand assets, from illustrations to brand shapes and patterns. As it's our primary color, we must use it sparingly to keep its impact wherever present.

texts.name: In the secondary colors, there are three tones. These three are used the most across the digital experience in many ways, so they must be applied correctly. We use them on all text, from headline titles to body copy and within iconography. Cosmos and Spotlight also comprise most of our backgrounds within the digital product.

texts.name: Our Tertiary colors are used a lot less across the digital landscape but, when used, play a vital part in the overall experience. For example, Earth is used on all Transactional Buttons. Ganymede forms part of the filtering experience and Mars is our error color.

texts.name: Accessibility is crucial to our digital experience. Using the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG), which explain how to make web content more accessible to all users, the use of our digital colors aim to be ㄸA compliant on contrast at all times. It뗩 the one that many organisations strive to meet, and Ticketmaster is no different. To help with this, and to support decisions, refer to the accessibility color sheet that lists out all the color combinations available and what needs to be taken into consideration to comply with our AA standard goal. If you have any doubt regarding the use of the color, whether it be in typography, backgrounds or new components, please speak to the Global Design System team.

texts.name: We use color hierarchy to help our fans process content within our digital designs. So whether we want a fan to notice the header first or the actions within the page depends on what color hierarchy we attach to each viewable piece of content. Having a good color hierarchy in place makes for an overall better experience and allows us to help guide our users through sometimes essential elements of content. Not following it can lead to users feeling confused and frustrated. To help avoid this, refer to the design examples and the color hierarchy table here.

texts.path: 游릭 Color Guidelines  > Color - Design Guide > Frame 16 > Frame 7242 > His work to date has
texts.characters: Harry Styles has established himself as one of the biggest and most influential artists in music.

texts.name: His work to date has
texts.path: 游릭 Color Guidelines  > Color - Design Guide > Frame 16 > Frame 7242 > His work to date has
texts.characters:
He recently released his record-setting No.1 new third album, Harry뗩 House to critical acclaim around the world. His self-titled debut solo album became one of the world뗩 top-ten best-selling albums of the year and had the biggest first week of sales by a male artist in history. 

His second album, Fine Line, topped the Billboard 200 when it was released, making it Harry뗩 second US Number One album, and made chart history providing the biggest sales week for a solo UK male artist since Nielsen Music began electronically trading sales data in 1991.
